  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "These acronyms represent different types of documents used in software and product development. They define the \"what,\" \"why,\" and \"how\" of a product or system.  Here's a breakdown of each, going roughly from high-level strategic vision to detailed technical specifications:\n\n*   **BRD - Business Requirements Document:** This document outlines the **business needs** that the product or project aims to address. It focuses on the **business goals, objectives, and problems** that the product needs to solve. It speaks from the perspective of the **business stakeholders**. It answers the questions:\n    *   *Why* are we building this?\n    *   *What* business problem are we solving?\n    *   *What* business value will it deliver?\n    *   *Who* are the target users (in a general, business-oriented sense)?\n    *   *How* will we measure success?\n    *   It generally avoids technical details.\n    *   **Example:** \"Increase customer retention by 15% within the next year by providing a more personalized onboarding experience.\"\n\n*   **MRD - Market Requirements Document:** The MRD focuses on **market needs and opportunities**. It analyzes the **market landscape, competition, and target audience** to define the **features and functionality** required to succeed in the market. It's closely aligned with product strategy and answers the questions:\n    *   *What* are the market trends driving this product?\n    *   *Who* are our competitors, and *what* are their strengths and weaknesses?\n    *   *What* are the key market segments we're targeting?\n    *   *What* features are necessary to be competitive in the market?\n    *   *What* is the market opportunity (size, growth potential)?\n    *   **Example:**  \"The market for AI-powered writing assistants is growing rapidly.  Competitors offer basic grammar and style checks, but lack advanced capabilities such as tone analysis and audience adaptation.  Our MRD calls for a product that excels in these areas, targeting professional writers and marketing teams.\"  The MRD might then specify that the product MUST integrate with Microsoft Word, Google Docs and other popular writing tools.\n\n*   **PRD - Product Requirements Document:** This document describes **what the product should do** from the user's perspective. It translates the business and market requirements into a detailed specification of the **features, functionality, and user experience** of the product. Think of it as a more specific elaboration of the MRD, and it often directly leads to the SRS. It answers the questions:\n    *   *What* are the specific features and functionality of the product?\n    *   *How* should users interact with the product?\n    *   *What* are the user stories or use cases that the product needs to support?\n    *   *What* are the acceptance criteria for each feature?\n    *   *What* are the non-functional requirements (performance, security, scalability)? (These are often touched upon but detailed in SRS)\n    *   **Example:** \"As a user, I want to be able to create a new blog post with a title, body, and tags.  I should be able to format the text using a WYSIWYG editor.  The system should automatically save drafts every 5 minutes.  Acceptance criteria: the editor should support basic formatting (bold, italics, headings, lists, links); the system should save drafts in the user's local storage; drafts should be recoverable after a browser crash.\"\n\n*   **FRS - Functional Requirements Specification:**  This document is often considered synonymous with SRS (see below), or sometimes used to describe a *section* within the SRS that focuses specifically on *functional* requirements. If considered distinct, it might be slightly less detailed than a full SRS.  It describes **what the system should do**, focusing on the specific **functions, features, and interactions** of the software. It's a more technical document than the PRD, detailing the inputs, outputs, and processes of each function.\n    *   **Example:** \"The system shall validate user input for the 'email' field against a regular expression to ensure it is a valid email address. The system shall display an error message if the input is invalid.\"\n\n*   **SRS - Software Requirements Specification:** This document is a comprehensive description of **how the software should be designed and implemented** to meet the requirements outlined in the BRD, MRD, and PRD. It is a technical document written for developers and testers. It includes:\n    *   **Functional Requirements:**  Detailed descriptions of what the software must do. (Overlaps heavily with FRS)\n    *   **Non-Functional Requirements:**  Qualities of the system, such as performance, security, scalability, usability, and reliability.\n    *   **Interface Requirements:**  How the software will interact with other systems, hardware, and users.\n    *   **Data Requirements:**  Structure and organization of data used by the system.\n    *   *Example*: \"The system shall authenticate users using OAuth 2.0. The system shall encrypt all sensitive data using AES-256 encryption. The system shall support at least 1,000 concurrent users with an average response time of less than 2 seconds.  The system must integrate with the existing CRM system via API calls.\"  The SRS would detail the specific API endpoints, data formats, security protocols, and performance benchmarks.\n\n*   **TRD - Technical Requirements Document:** This document specifies the **technical infrastructure, platform, and tools** required to build and deploy the product or system. It includes details about the:\n    *   Hardware and software requirements\n    *   Network infrastructure\n    *   Database specifications\n    *   Security requirements\n    *   Deployment environment\n    *   Coding standards\n    *   It might also specify preferred vendors, technologies, and architectural patterns.\n    *   **Example:** \"The system shall be deployed on AWS using EC2 instances and RDS databases. The system shall use Docker containers for packaging and deployment. The system shall use Git for version control and Jenkins for continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD). All code must adhere to the company's coding standards for Python as documented on the internal wiki.\"\n\n**Relationship and Flow:**\n\nGenerally, the documents are created in a sequence, with each building upon the previous one.  A simplified flow is often:\n\n1.  **BRD** (Why are we doing this?)\n2.  **MRD** (What are the market needs?)\n3.  **PRD** (What should the product do?)\n4.  **SRS/FRS** (How should the software be implemented to meet the PRD?)\n5.  **TRD** (What technical infrastructure is needed?)\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Context is Key:** The specific content and format of these documents will vary depending on the size and complexity of the project, the company's development methodology, and the industry.\n*   **Overlap and Consolidation:**  In some cases, two or more of these documents might be combined into a single document, particularly for smaller projects.  For example, a very small project might combine the MRD and PRD.\n*   **Agile Development:** In agile environments, these documents are often more lightweight and iterative.  User stories and acceptance criteria may be captured in a backlog rather than in a formal PRD.\n*   **Living Documents:** These documents should be considered \"living\" documents that are updated and revised throughout the development process.\n*   **Communication:** The primary purpose of these documents is to facilitate communication and collaboration among stakeholders, including business stakeholders, product managers, developers, testers, and designers.\n\nIn summary, each document plays a distinct role in defining the requirements for a product or system, ensuring that all stakeholders are aligned and that the final product meets the business needs and user expectations.  The BRD sets the stage, the MRD validates market fit, the PRD defines the product's functionality, the SRS/FRS specifies the software implementation, and the TRD outlines the technical environment.\n",
